         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">23/9/76. ¶  ¶ Is it not likely, my dear Mr Bentham, that Acacia Farnesiana must be regarded as of eastern Origin. It is clearly the shrub, which Dioscorides &amp; Theophrastos knew from Egypt and Kappadoc...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.09.23c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 185.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">23/9/76.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Is it not likely, my dear Mr Bentham, that <name key="Acacia%20Farnesiana">Acacia Farnesiana</name> must be regarded as of eastern Origin. It is clearly the shrub, which Dioscorides &amp; Theophrastos knew from Egypt and Kappadocia.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated by Bentham</seg>:</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.7874in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">Cappadocian [Acacia] of Dioscorides from his vague description is probably the plant to which it is referred by Mathioli comm. Diosc. 176 [i.e. Mattioli (1565)] where it is figured and which is evidently the [Cytisus].</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.7874in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">The Aegyptian Dioscorides or [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">illegible word</seg>] Aegyptus of Theophrast[os] is probably correctly referred by Bodaeus in his Commentary on Thephrast 1644, 310 as the Acacia arabica or nilotica which he there figured [i.e. Theophrastus (1644)].</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See G. Bentham to M, 30 April 1877.</p>
               </note> It is moreover, just such a plant, as the Spaniards in their conquest would carry with them, like <name key="Ceratonia%20Siliqua">Ceratonia Siliqua</name>, and it would disseminate itself even easier than the Ceratonia.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, ﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽﷽; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
